locality:  NA, occurrenceRemarks: The image contains a commin plant that I have positively identified as being within the Genus of Galax. The plant is green wit a large simple leaf and rigid edges, and hs one leaf per stem and is in a small cluster (numerous plants of the same species are within the image). This plant is located in a deciduous forest, obscured location, withun partial to complete shade, and wet to moist. Additionally, the leaf is more rounded but seems as if it is consistent of a geart shaoe but with two lobes. This is a herbaceous and evergreen plant that is codified as perennial and is common within the regions that I have identified it within; the plant can be flund in the Appalachian mountians (the general region in which this plant was located) and at regions up to 1,500 meters. I believe that this plats taxonomic nomenclature is Galax urceolata., verbatimLocality: North Carolina, US

locality:  NA, occurrenceRemarks: "Galax, Galax urceolata, the wandplant, [Coltsfoot?], wandflower, or beetleweed, is a genus in the flowering plant family Diapensiaceae, containing a single species, Galax urceolata (syn. G. rotundifolia, G. aphylla). It is native to the southeastern United States from Massachusetts and New York south to northern Alabama, growing mainly in the Appalachian Mountains at altitudes of up to 1,500 m, where it grows in shaded places in forests. (Source: Wikipedia, Galax, CC BY-SA 3.0)" https://plants.ces.ncsu.edu/plants/galax-urceolata/ Galax is a North Carolina native that exhibits shiny, long-stalked, roundish heart-shaped leaves, 2-5 in. wide. It is a perennial with bright green leaves in summer that become bronzed to reddish in winter. Small white feathery flowers arranged in a narrow cluster on a naked stalk rise above the leaves in late spring or early summer. The flower stalks are 8-15 inches high. Galax prefers cool, moist sites with partial shade. It is common to the NC mountains and Piedmont, but unusual in the coastal areas. It grows in slow expanding clumps and its flowers attract bees. "It has also been used in herbalism to treat cuts and kidney ailments." Observed in NC piedmont, not too distant from Marion, in December., verbatimLocality: Pisgah National Forest, Old Fort, NC, US
